<Base
  title="The math behind the crisis-surcharge · Anubhav Das"
  description="Across five carriers in May 2026, a line item labelled 'fuel' came to contain a great deal more than fuel. The pass-through math, the 22-year ratchet, and where the argument can be challenged."
>
  <div class="progress" aria-hidden="true"><div class="progress__track"></div><div class="progress__fill" id="progress-fill"></div></div>

  <main id="main" tabindex="-1">
    <!-- TITLE CARD -->
    <header class="scene" aria-labelledby="art-title">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="kicker reveal">
          <span class="kicker__num" aria-hidden="true">05</span>
          <span class="kicker__meta">Analysis &nbsp;/&nbsp; May 2026 &nbsp;/&nbsp; 3 figures &nbsp;/&nbsp; 12 min</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="article-title reveal" id="art-title">The math behind the crisis-surcharge.</h1>
        <p class="standfirst reveal">Across five carriers in May 2026, a line item labelled <em class="accent">&ldquo;fuel&rdquo;</em> came to contain a great deal more than fuel. Here is the pass-through math, the 22-year ratchet, and where the argument can be challenged.</p>
      </div>
    </header>

    <!-- LEAD -->
    <div class="col first">
      <p class="lead reveal">The Strait of Hormuz closed at the end of February 2026, jet kerosene ran to roughly ninety percent above its five-year average, and every carrier reached for the same instrument: the fuel surcharge. This is a note about what actually sits inside that number once you do the hedge-adjusted arithmetic, and about a mechanism that, by design, resists ever coming back down.</p>
      <p class="reveal">Start from one publicly disclosed hedge book. A Northwestern flagship's Q1 2026 deck reports an effective fuel cost moving from $792 to $1,260 a tonne while holding a 70% hedge, a +59% effective increase against +97% unhedged spot. Scale that, carrier by carrier, into a <em>fair</em> pass-through: the per-passenger figure that would just recover the fuel-price move. Then set it beside what each carrier actually published.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- KEY-FIGURE BAND -->
    <section class="evidence" aria-label="Published surcharge divided by fair pass-through, by carrier">
      <div class="figures reveal">
        <div class="fig"><div class="fig__n">0.69&times;</div><div class="fig__k">Northwestern<br>FRA&ndash;JFK</div></div>
        <div class="fig"><div class="fig__n">1.23&times;</div><div class="fig__k">Far Eastern<br>HKG&ndash;LHR</div></div>
        <div class="fig"><div class="fig__n">3.10&times;</div><div class="fig__k">Tokyo hub<br>NRT&ndash;LHR</div></div>
        <div class="fig is-verdict"><div class="fig__n">13&times;</div><div class="fig__k">Gulf flagship<br>DXB&ndash;JFK</div></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="col">
      <p class="reveal">Two carriers under-recover even on the fuel portion alone. One sits near fair. And two, Tokyo hub and the Gulf flagship, land far above anything a fuel move can explain. Below two times, structural cost recovery (currency, ETS, distribution, disruption) is a plausible account of the gap. Above it, the label stops describing its contents.</p>
    </div>

